Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[When last reported by ProMed-mail in mid-February 2009 (Meningitis,
meningococcal - India (04): (NE) 20090217.0661), there were said to
be 165 deaths in Meghalaya in just the 1st month of 2009; whereas, the
current report above says that there were only 127 deaths in Meghalaya
in all of the 1st 6 months of 2009. In mid-February 2009, the epidemic
also involved neighboring Indian states of Tripura and Mizoram, as
well as an adjacent region (Chittagong Hill Tracts) of Bangladesh.
Meningococcal serogroup A was said to be the culprit. At that time,
ProMED-mail reported that a vaccination program was underway, and from
the current report is still underway.

Meghalaya, a mountainous Indian state, is located between the
northeastern border of Bangladesh and the Indian state of Assam. A
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of India that shows the states
of Meghalaya, Tripura, and Mizoram can be found at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?v=22.9,79.6,5>.
A map of Bangladesh showing the location of the Chittagong Hill Tracts
that borders the Indian state of Mizoram can be found at
<http://www.traveljournals.net/explore/bangladesh/map/m3773498/chittagong_hill_tract.html>. -
Mod.ML]
